editorialSummary.text: Fast-food chain serving Mexican-inspired fare such as tacos, quesadillas & nachos.

originalText.text: the cultural of appropriation has never tasted better if you need a massive influx of calories & sodium in the form of Mexican-ish inspired food. BUT tbh, there’s no real cultural appropriation bc if you’ve been to Mexico then you know how great Mexican cuisine is and how varied the types of foods eaten there are…and Taco Bell has appropriated nothing except some food terms. but i digress…this location  is a fast food oasis in the Gramercy / Stuy area serving up tacos, burritos, quesadillas, nachos, hybrids combos of the aforementioned and more! the narrow interior is pretty big bc it stretches far back from the street providing a good amount of seating. it’s always been clean and well-maintained when i have stopped by. most people order via the touchscreen even though you can order via the counter. the touchscreen allow customization and swapping things in  an order versus the likeliness of human error via the counter if you tried some complex order. food comes out hot and fast and you can watch your order being made bc the prep station is viewable. last time i stopped here, got one of the Crave Boxes after an insane day of endless tasks and not eating—got a much-needed 1300+ calories via Chalupa, burrito, taco,  chips, and drink…it satisfied the hunger pangs as only over-processed meats, fats, cheeses, carbs, etc. can do— and i regret none of it! the service is quick and friendly. the crowd here is mostly local workers, residents, and tourists from other neighborhoods like me. Taco Bell used to be a guiltier cheaper pleasures of the fast food world just a few years ago but that ain’t the case no mo’. yeah yeah inflation, supply chains, excuses, corporate greed and the dollar buys way less than it did just a few years ago. while Taco Bell prolly isn’t the best thing for you, it’s certainly not the worst. Moderation yo!
